    <node id="B_S0">
      <data key="d0">sentence</data>
      <data key="d1">Based on the presented symptoms, the first clinical suspicion should be Meralgia Paresthetica (3- Radiated low back pain / lumbosciatica), given that the pain is localized to the lateral aspect of the…</data>
    </node>
    <node id="B_S1">
      <data key="d0">sentence</data>
      <data key="d1">Meralgia paresthetica involves compression or trauma to the lateral femoral cutaneous nerve, causing symptoms similar to those described.</data>
    </node>
    <node id="B_S2">
      <data key="d0">sentence</data>
      <data key="d1">However, it's important to consider alternative diagnoses such as radiculopathy (due to her history of metabolic syndrome and the radiating nature of the pain), and sciatica (3- Radiated low back pain…</data>
    </node>
